{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_goosefoot_ver01/data/sn84036285/00340581829/1930081401/0663.xml":{"full_text":"Carbon County News\nPublished every Thursday at Red Lodge, Carbon Co.,\nOFFICIAL PAPER OP CARBON COU NTY\nOFFICIAL PAPER OF THE CITY OF RED LODGE, MONT.\nO. H. P. SHELLEY, Editor and Owner\nEntered at the Postoffice at\nRed Lodge, Montana, as Mat\nter of the Second Class. Un\nder the Act of Congress of\nMarch 5, 1879.\nMontana\nSubscription Per year,\n$2.50; six months,\nthree months, $1.\nscriptions payable in advance\n$1.50;\nAll sub\nMember^gl93Q\n51\n23s\n\u00eewrfofr\nNational Editorial Association\nAdvertising rates based on guaranteed circulation and furnished\nupon application. Discount given on contracts.\nnt ga pfe rr 4\n\nHow long IS a mile? asks a western editor. Mell\n\u00eet depends on whether it is a concrete or a dirt road.\nT\nIt IS said that most of our prisons are too small\nand this is probably true. And to the boys inside it\nwould be difficult to build them SO big that\nwouldn't be too small. 1\nTELEPHONE NUMBER NINE\n-0\n0\nStill the situation is not without some consola\ntion, even for th fanners, if the price of wheat is\ndown, a bushel of it will still buy about as many gal\nlons of gas as in the days before the war.\n-j-,\nAll .Europe, Canada and Australia are complain\ning loudly of depression, and as soon as the Demo\ncratic national, committee's publicity gets around to\nit the whole thing will be blamed on the extra territ\norial effects of the new tariff law.\n-o\nIf President Hoover wants to learn on his vaca\ntion, just how the country ought to be run, all he has\nto do is slip into the Pullman smoking compartment\nand listen to the conversation for an hour or so.\n\u25a0O\n-0\nThe government of Spain has announced tariff)\nincreases, with the explanation that it is not an act of\nreprisal for the new Ai\nlean tariff, which is prob\nably true because the Spanish tariff was already the\nhighest in the world and nearly twice as high as the\nAmerican tariff.\nn v\n-0\nA great many of our professional liberals in Am-\nerica seem to think that all prisoners in American\njails should be released but you won't hear many of\nthem protesting against the shipping of convict-made\ngoods from Russia to America.\n--o\nPresident Nicholas Murray Butler of Columbia\nUniversity asks the American people to consider tol\nerantly the noble experiment in Russia, but it is\ndoubtful if they will do it although the first thing the\n\"bolsheviks did was to kill most of the college profes\nsors, and muzzle the rest.\nHOOVER IN '32\nSenator Royal S. Copeland, Democrat, of New\nYork, if he is quoted correctly in the New York\nTimes, places a desire for returning prosperity in this\ncountry above politics. Furthmore, the New York\nSenator has proclaimed his- faith in an early return\nof prosperity. He said, addressing a meeting in New\nYork of representatives of the garment trade:\nFor as sure as fate the chimneys will be smok\nand the crops will be good and will bring good\nces in 1932 and Hoover will be re-elected.\nSome of his audience, perhaps, considering the\nmocratic source of this remark, laughed. But Sen-j\nor Copeland added, \"That's serious.\"\u2014Washington!\nvening Star, Independent.\nc\n\n1\n-O\nBUILDING AND PROSPERITY\n\nLast year's total of homes built in the United\n\"States sank to the lowest level since 1921, and this\nyear will doubtless establish the home building low\nwater mark for a decade.\nLast year's shortage may have been due to a\ntightening of credit because of the great volume of\nmoney diverted to speculation. There is no money\nshortage at this time, and the unwillingness of fi\nnancial institutions to let loose of cash for home con\nstruction must be due more to apprehension than to\nactual conditions.\nThese apprehensions have chiefly been caused by\nspeculative building in the larger cities, where the\nconstruction of houses beyond the needs of the pop\nulation has caused shrinkage in values.\nSuch apprehension does not properly apply to\nhome building in the settled smaller cities of assured\nfuture. There are few safer risks than homes oc\ncupied by owners, about which their family life is\nbuilt.\nFrom both an economic and a social standpoint\nthe halt in the progress of home construction is to be\ndeplored. The home is our strongest social cement.\nPretty hard to make a revolutionary out of a home\nowner. Moreover a shortage of proper housing af\nfects materially the industrial efficiency of a com\nmunity. More important still, comfbrtable homes\nORGANIZED LABOR'S DEMANDS\nMET IN SMOOT-HAWLEY BILL\n_I\nORGANIZED LABOR AM) AG\nHELPED\nFRAME TARIFF BILL FOR\nFIRST TIME IN HISTORY OF\nIN\nH AYE\nCULIT RE\nLEGISLATION\nTARIFF\nTHIS COUNTRY\nRepresentative John Q. Tilson.\nRepublican Floor Leader has call-!\ned attention to the enactment ot\ntariff duties in response to the de\nmands of organized labor for ad\nditiona protection to the products\nand industries in which they were,\nparticularly interested as wage,\nearners.\nAfter calling attention to the in\ncreased duties on agricultural pro-1\n\nducts in answer to the sentiment\namong farmers and Others, Con-|f\nK\u00ab*;man Tilson went on to say:\nIost ot the important increases\nin duty on manufactured articles\ni\" ere made on the requested of in\ni r ?\u00a3SglS' \u00efJ r h waf par\nthey.ticularly interested were boots and\n(shoes, leather, bricks, marble,!^\ngranite, patterns, bottles, antique\nfurniture, straw and felt hats,\n\nprint rollers, wall paper, pottery,\nflint and window glass, woven wire\ncloth, and printed matter. The la\nbor organizations which urged and\nobtained either new duties or in\ncreased duties on these items in\ncluded the Boot and Shoe Workers\nUnion, the Brick and Clay Work\ners Union, the Glass Bottle Blow\ners Union, the Potters Union, the\nUnited Hatters of North America,!\nthe American Flint Glass Workers\nUnion, the Bricklajers, Masons,)\nand Plasterers International\nUnion, Brotherhood of Painters,\nPaper Hangers and Decorators,\nPatte Makers League, u P hois-|\nuniM^\u00efpJ^!\ner Crafts, and the American wire\nWeavers association.\nmm\n-..-A\ny\nryj\nm\n\nI\nI\nIMAGES.\nI^ODEO*\n\n9\nMS\n\u00ff l\n\nfvGRICUmiRI\n'M\ni\ny\nyiREWDRKS\nE0\u00bbN6\nBOUT\nV\nVN\nT M\nMO\n\nff\n3\nr\nY\n\nI\nN*.\nw.\nPi:\n\n\u00c9\u00d4\nft\n15\nl\nHJ\nV-'\n.AI\nare the greatest contribution ibis possible to make to\nthe happiness of humans.\nThis is of course not a local, but a national ques\ntion. The stoppages of the flow of credit come from\nthe top of our financial system down. In so far as\nthe national government may exert influence, it\nought to be in behalf of a loosening of credit for home\nand industrial construction, whatever limitations are\nplaced in speculative ventures either in construction\nor otherwise. A half billion dollars lent by the gov\nernment to build homes would probably do more to\npromote wheat prices by putting home consumers\nat work than any effort to directly boost the price of\nwheat. Idle workmen and their families are not\ngood at consuming a wheat surplus.\nThe effect of our vast national and state pro\ngrams of public construction is small as compared\nwith that of normal home construction. Last year's\nslow-down would justify great expansion of activity\nalong this line this year and next. That expansion\nwould do much to alleviate the employment situation.\nrSUliamg materials are at a lower price at this\ntime than in several years. Now would be the best\ni y, v a'nuvv vvuuiu\ntime to ouilQ tor anyone who wishes to insure con-!\nstruction at low comparative cost. Financial insti\nUnions shoulci be pm m a position to meet the demand\nfor building by persons wishing to construct homes,\nhut unable to do so except on a basis of deferred pay\nments for much of the investment required.\nne\"' i aw a so carries in it a\nprovision to eliminate within a\nperiod of 18 months competition\nw ith products made by\nconvict,\nforced, and indenture labor in Eu\nrcpe an i d th Orient, which was\nP r \u00b0P ose( aR\u20ac indorsed by labor\nSroups.\nFor the first time in tariff leg\nislation organized labor and or\nganized agriculture have taken an\naetive t in frandng a tariff laW(\nand in an overwhelming number of\ncases have obtained the help they\naskcd It is too much to expect\nsingle grou should be entir -l\ne satisfied with the law as a\nwhole It is impogsible for 435\nmembers of the House and 96\nmembers of the Senate to ag ree\non a law which entirely meets the\nviews of any person or any one\nT. w u nlo\ns fa vo rable to both labor and ag\nric u*ture and is beneficial to our\nindustrial interests.\nSeveral millions of good Ameri\ncan W age-earners are represented\n1 Tison* Thev\nYj very impo-nnt cross section\ntfc\u00e7 indu8tria y[ fe of thenat i oa\nard\narc fully entitled to protec\ntien from the cheap labor of other\nnat\nIa Vy 27 there were 45 establish,\nm\nin the brick industry, em\nploying 790 workers at wages of\n$1,051,000 and a production of $3.\n616,000; 1,846 establishments en\ngaed in clay products, 100,972\nworkers at wages of $121,967,000,\nproducing $319,908,000; glass, 919\nplants and 74,598 workers with\nwages of $93,928,000, and a pro\nduction cf $336,147,000; potteries\nnumbered\ners. wages of $45,150,000, and pio\nAluction cf $110,597,000; boots and\n203 110 wages 225 090 000\nble works, 1,978 establishments,\n6 with 36,667 work\nshoes, factories 1,357, workers,\nmar\n40,474 workers, wages $68,491,000.\nMiss Helene Rowland and Bob\nby Rowland of Bearcreek were in\nRed Lodge on business Monday.\nSawyer Ban Lifted\nNotice is hereby given that the,\nSawyer Stores, Inc., have signed,\nthe Union wage agreement and are,\ntherefore declared to be fair to\nUnion labor. This is to rescind\nprevious action of the Unions and\nto remove all opposition of organ-1\nized labor,\nLocal No. 1771, U. M. W. of\nA., Red Lodge, Montana,\nLocal No. 2659, U. M .W. of\nA., Bearcreek, Montana,\nLocal No. 858, l M. W. of A.,\nA., Bearcreek. Montana,\nLocal No. 4457, U. M. W. of\nBearcreek. Montana,\nLocal No. 1729, U. M. W. of\nA., Bearcreek, Montana.\nm\n4\n\n\"i 1 6 J\nThere's no fun in danc\ning or anything else when\nyour feet hurt! Nyal\nCorn Remover stops pain\nimmediately. A few ap\nplications banish corns\nand callouses. Then feet\nare happy. In applicator\nbottle, 25c, For perspir\ning feet use Nyal Eas'Em\nFoot Pewdcr.\nm\nVf\u00bb\na\nvrv\nLve coto\ntoners\n0 cc vwv*\n-itttW\u00dc\u00cf\nJ\n0 T\nV'Y\n0 ov V\n[K\nPS\nJ t\nCORN REMOVER\nEvery Nyal Druggist is tne proprietor o! his own slom\nand a registered pharmacist\u2014skilled in his profession.\nWhispering Baritone Wins\nBy Novelty of His Music\nW\nw\nw\n3\nm\n\"7\not\nm\nV\n\nr/y\n\ntlo\n\"\u2022r\nQ&VS\n\n5%\n\nm\nY/\nft\na\nft\nft\n\u00c6\nX\n\u00c6m\nI\nft.\n9\nWb\nVa\n\nmi\n\u00ffi.Y\n[.m\nf&U\n/ft\n\u25a0m\nmm\nm\nm- -1\nm\nY v\nft\n\nJ\n\n\ny\nA\n7\nvi -V:\nm\n\ns/j\nm\nf P)\ny\nm\nA\nT\nv A; ftt:\n\n\n\n\n\n/j\nff\u00df\nm\ni:y|.\nv\nf\nc\ni\ns\n1\no%\n1\n1\n0/\nA\n\nA\n\nv J\nm\n-7\\\nm\n\u25a0yr\n\ns\nV,\n'NX\nm\ntIAGJ\u00cf SMITH\ny\n\nSr y\n'il\nj.-l\nEE\nf\nlove made a. ^f' s y ouh o\u00a3 nie, Tlie on- ly l '<i 2 1 real-ly cere for.\nNow York city. Many an\nAmerican singer has puzzled in\nof one Jack Smith, more generally\nl \u00eeno T Y the Y hisp fY g bar i_\ntone who has captured the music\n'Rails of eight foreign countries,\n\u00c4\u00c4S\"\nEngland and in France, hut in\n\u00c4SE' H\na follow artist, just returned\nS itfi\nJack Smith Has Fans\nYi Eight Foreign\nCountries\nE. B. Merrill 1 Bridger attorney,\nwas in Red Lodge on business\nMonday.\nJoe Kuchinski of Bridger was a\ncounty seat visitor Monday.\nNOTICE\nTo all Republican Precinct Com -1\nNotice is hereby given that\nthere will be a meeting of the Rc\npublcian\nCarbon county on the 15th day of\nAugust, 1930,\nmitteemen ai^l Candidates of\nCarbon County, Montana.\nCentral Committee of\nat 1 o clock P. M.\nin the court room at the Carbon\nCounty Court House at Red Lodge,\nMontana, for the purpose of or\nganizing for the\ncoming campaign\nand election of officers and trans\nacting any other business\nmay come before said meeting.\nJ. G. SKINNER, Chairman,\nJ. H. Honkala, Sec'y.\n1st pub., Aug. 7, 1930.\n2nd pub., Aug. 14, 1930.\nwhich\ncomes from a most reliable source,\nthe lips ox persons who, with him,\nhave been part of Smith's audi\nences.\n\"Europeans are used to hearing\na male singer open his mouth and\nsend forth the fullest volume of\nvoice he can set free,\" says this\nbystander. \"Smith first startled,\nthen delighted them with his soft\nquiet singing. So effortless is the\nsinging that, as the singer's nick\nname implies, it is almost a whis\nper. The Europeans like the\nchange. They have hoard thunder\ning baritones all their lives. They\nfind Jack's technique restful, in\ntriguing, and above all, novel, es\npecially in such soft enchanting\nmelodics as 'Love Made A Gypsy\nOut Of Me,' which has become In\nternational in its popularity.\"\n\"inter Garden Revue Said lo Be\nOne Of The Largest Musical\nComedies On The Road\nThe Winter Garden revue hail\ned as the newest venture of theat\nrical producers to offer outdoor aud\niences a metropolitan musical pro\nduction, will head the evening en\ntertainment features provided for\nthe 1930 Midland Empire fair, ac- 4\ncording to an announcement made\nof J. M. Bresnahan, manager of\nthe exposition.\nCarrying two carloads of equip\nment, the revue company is said to\nbe one of the largest traveling nuis\nical comedy aggregations on the\nroad and lists a east of 29 persons.\nThe complete equipment makes\npossible an entirely different out\nof doors presentation than has been\noffered in past years, according to\nMr. Bresnahan, who said the fair\nboard had engaged the revue only\nafter a thorough study of its pos\nsibilities as an amusement attrac\ntion.\nIt is the first time in the history\nof the fair, according to officials,\nthat a musical extravaganza has\nbeen engaged to headline grand\nstand attractions. In addition to\nthe stage production, Thearle-Duf\nfield fireworks spectacle will be giv\nen every evening except Wednes\nday night, when the American Le\ngion boxing show will hold undi\nvided attention of fair patrons.\nLighting effects for the musical\nrevue are more efficient than any\nillumination system heretofore\navailable for outdoor productions,\nwhile two stages are used to as\nsure ample space back of the cur\ntain line for both crews of stage\nhands and performers, it was said.\nThe company carries its own\nswitchboard, foot, spot, flood and\nborder lights with thorough illum\nination to all parts of the stages,\nwhile three microphones, arranged\nbefore the 60-foot stage front, car\nry the voices of principals and chor\nus to all parts of the grandstand.\nAccording to Edgar I. Sehooley,\nproducer of the revue, elaborate\ncostumes and lavish scenery are\nprovided to give the production an\nair equal to many high-class New\nYork stage extraganzas.\nThe revue is enacted on two lev\nel stages. Huge curtains, extend\ning the width of the stage front,\nenhance the \"inside theatre'' effect\nwhich complete musical scores and\nthe quick changes in numbers is\nsaid to give the production a\nsmoothness not heretofore seen in\noutdoor shows.\nTechnique in development of tht\noutdoor revue has progressed slow\nly, according to a communication\nfrom Mr. Sehooley, who declares\nthat this type of entertainment has\nachieved wide popularity with fail\nand exposition patrons.\nSchooley's revue is an annua\nspectacle at many of the largei\neastern fairs and local officials are\njubilant at being able to bring the\nproduction to the coming Midland\nEmpire fair. The local grandstand\nholds approximately 10,000 persons\nand Mr. Bresnahan said the factor\nwas a strong point in the board's\ndecision to contract the revue. A\npopular admission charge of 2\u00a3\ncents will be made for the evening\ngrandstand entertainment program\naccording to the fair manager, whe\nannounced that no reservations\nother than box seats would be mack\nfor the night show.\n0\nNew Administration Building At\nFair Grounds To Be Occupied\nAfter August 10th\nBillings\u2014Administrative and ex\necutive offices of the Midland Em\npire fair will be installed in their\nnew home in the now nearly com\npleted administration building by\nAugust 10.\nThe building will accommodate\nthe office of Manager J. M. Bres\nnahan and his personal staff and\nalso will provide space for various\ndepartmental bureaus which hereto\nfore have been scattered in widely\nseparated fairgrounds buildings, it\nwas said.\nAmong units to have space in the\nnew building, will be the general\ncashier's department, entry clerks,\nconcessions department, and ticket\nsales department. Provisions for\nthe board's publicity bureau and a\ngeneral information counter also\nwill be made. In the past, the in\nformation counter has occupied\nspace in the auditorium building,\nThe office of the racing and\nrodeo department will be contin\nued in rooms under the grand\nstand, it was announced. This bu\nreau is one of the largest of fair\ntime departments and handles all\nentries in both track and rodeo\ndivisions.\nThe administration building is\none of the two new units to be\nstructed this year. A 60-stable live-\nstock barn is now completed and\nready for occupancy. Total cost oi\nthe two buildings was placed bj\nfair officials at \u00a710,000.\ncon-","height":"21486","width":"15486"}}
